        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-10-30T12:25:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-10-30T12:25:00-05:00" n="248"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d248">
                <head>248. Memorandum of a Telephone Conversation Between the Under Secretary of
                    State for Political Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>)
                    and the President’s Special Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName
                        corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d248fn1">Source: Library of Congress, <persName corresp="#p_HWA1"
                            >Harriman</persName> Papers, Telephone Conversations. Transcribed by
                        Dolores <gloss target="#t_P1">P</gloss> Perruso of <persName
                            corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>’s staff.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1963-10-30T12:25:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 30, 1963—12:25 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said he had had a talk after
                        <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName> left about <persName
                        corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> and the Embassy. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said he had been reading the
                        telegrams.<note n="2" xml:id="d248fn2">Apparent reference to <ref
                            target="#d240">Documents 240</ref>, <ref target="#d246">246</ref>, and
                            <ref target="#d247">247</ref>.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> was indignant <persName
                        corresp="#p_HGPD1">Harkins</persName> was not asked about military
                    assessment… .<note n="3" xml:id="d248fn3">Ellipsis in the source text.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said <persName
                        corresp="#p_HGPD1">Harkins</persName>’ assessment is not accurate. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said he thought <persName
                        corresp="#p_BMG1">Bundy</persName> should bear this in mind in connection
                    with what he might say. <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said he
                    had a great deal of misgivings about the competence of <persName
                        corresp="#p_HGPD1">Harkins</persName>’ staff. He said he thought Trueheart
                    has done a good job.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
